WEBVTT

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.890
>> Thank you, and welcome to the IT State of Union.

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:31.010
Today, I'm going to talk about
trends in IT, and more specifically,

00:00:31.010 --> 00:00:34.770
one specific trend, which is the consumerization of IT.

00:00:34.770 --> 00:00:41.210
So, what I'm going to do is we're going
to go through four different areas,

00:00:41.210 --> 00:00:45.380
and we'll look at how consumer products
have changed the face of IT and the way

00:00:45.380 --> 00:00:49.580
that we work, and we'll start off with storage.

00:00:49.579 --> 00:00:58.030
So, storage is the growth in storage is not
just limited to back-end service anymore,

00:00:58.030 --> 00:01:03.719
and in fact the back-end storage is very expensive,
so this is creating some interesting problems.

00:01:03.719 --> 00:01:12.150
Gardener, actually, in a recent survey, said that
93 percent of corporate data is now at the edge.

00:01:12.150 --> 00:01:17.190
In addition, corporate data, the data types
that we're using, is becoming consumerized

00:01:17.189 --> 00:01:23.819
as we're introducing more complex kinds of data, the
use of video, complex presentations, and so forth.

00:01:23.819 --> 00:01:29.479
So, the data itself is becoming consumerized,
and because all this data is out on the edge,

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:36.079
we now find that work critical and life critical
data is often residing on the same system.

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:42.870
Now, with a large growth of data, easy
access to this data is crucial, and in fact,

00:01:42.870 --> 00:01:49.960
we see that your market response time is actually
proportional to the amount of time it takes

00:01:49.959 --> 00:01:57.179
to access your data, so therefore accessing the data quickly
is becoming increasingly important for your enterprise.

00:01:58.290 --> 00:02:05.860
The other interesting feature that is going on with
storage is that with traditional storage systems,

00:02:05.859 --> 00:02:12.729
the cost of maintaining those storage systems frequently
exceeds the cost of replacing them, and so the whole picture

00:02:12.729 --> 00:02:17.329
around the TCO of your storage system is changing.

00:02:20.039 --> 00:02:23.219
Now, this is actually the storage that's being purchased.

00:02:23.219 --> 00:02:24.789
This is not the existing storage.

00:02:24.789 --> 00:02:28.849
So, this is just a graph of the growth of storage,

00:02:28.849 --> 00:02:35.079
and some customers that we see are easily seeing 100
percent growth per year on their storage requirements,

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:38.110
and these are people like, you know,
the video post production, broadcasting,

00:02:38.110 --> 00:02:41.820
print and publishing, people who
are dealing with rich media.

00:02:41.819 --> 00:02:49.009
Now, the other interesting thing is that costs are
going down, and this is due to people like Apple,

00:02:49.009 --> 00:02:57.819
who are introducing consumer or commodity based products
to be able to have a significant decrease in costs,

00:02:57.819 --> 00:03:04.129
and in fact, not only are we driving the costs of
storage, but driving the industries cost of storage

00:03:04.129 --> 00:03:08.199
down because we're using sort of consumer like drives.

00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:11.930
Excuse me.

00:03:13.330 --> 00:03:15.440
Now, I talked about content.

00:03:15.439 --> 00:03:20.310
There are many different data types, and the data that
we're using in storage is getting more and more complex.

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:26.340
We start off with simple email, although that
is even, even that's sort of become richer.

00:03:26.340 --> 00:03:35.659
We're going from plain text to html kinds of things, words,
photos, podcasts which starts including video and QuickTime,

00:03:35.659 --> 00:03:40.590
Keynote actually is a very rich
medium, so that data type is expanding,

00:03:40.590 --> 00:03:45.259
and then high definition movies,
which is the largest of that set.

00:03:45.259 --> 00:03:51.719
And the interesting thing is that with all this
consumer data size exploding, even the small data,

00:03:51.719 --> 00:03:59.000
such as your email, is now carrying a lot of this other
stuff as a payload, so even that is exploding also.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:04.620
And enterprise data is really following
suit as IT users become more creative

00:04:04.620 --> 00:04:07.879
in the way that they present corporate data.

00:04:09.289 --> 00:04:19.480
As an example, we have NFL films, and their network where
they were trying to make all their live footage available

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:24.569
to their live shows from the various different games
to their live shows immediately as it happened,

00:04:24.569 --> 00:04:27.800
and they had an old infrastructure that just couldn't scale.

00:04:27.800 --> 00:04:35.470
And so they installed XN on a 54 terabyte ApplTe
storage system, and they're expecting that to double.

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:42.160
So, we provided a scalable system at a commodity
kind of pricing that made it affordable for them.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:46.630
In addition, they used the QuickTime formats,
which are available on all platforms,

00:04:46.629 --> 00:04:51.839
so they had this ubiquitous format that
they could then distribute their data with,

00:04:51.839 --> 00:04:57.929
and for extensibility with Final Cut Pro, the xml project
exchange allowed them to merge things like game stance

00:04:57.930 --> 00:05:04.819
with the media as it was being distributed, and then
make it immediately available to their TV programs.

00:05:04.819 --> 00:05:10.800
So, you can see how this consumer based
technologies, or consumer oriented

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:18.449
or driven technologies can turn an enterprise solution,
and make it cost effective and rapidly deployable.

00:05:21.449 --> 00:05:23.870
So that's storage.

00:05:23.870 --> 00:05:29.730
Now, you have all this storage, what do you do with it?

00:05:29.730 --> 00:05:31.210
We need to consume it.

00:05:31.209 --> 00:05:33.750
And that's what distribution is about.

00:05:35.490 --> 00:05:37.629
So, what we're talking about is not publishing, right,

00:05:37.629 --> 00:05:42.949
and so today we have multiple different
devices to consume this data.

00:05:42.949 --> 00:05:52.920
Data is richer and bigger, we've got movies, we have
music, we have photos, and we have to deliver it

00:05:52.920 --> 00:05:57.819
to multiple different devices, whether
that's your iPod, whether it's your computer,

00:05:57.819 --> 00:06:06.290
whether it's the large screen TV, and time from
receiving this data to distribution, is shrinking.

00:06:06.290 --> 00:06:11.280
You cannot wait and sit and process this data
and sit on it, you have to be able to send it

00:06:11.279 --> 00:06:12.750
out to the people that need to consume it.

00:06:12.750 --> 00:06:17.860
And this is true regardless of whether it's a
consumer, or whether it's in your enterprise.

00:06:19.980 --> 00:06:25.590
Now, this is an interesting little graph, to show you
what I mean by the explosion of the rich data types,

00:06:25.589 --> 00:06:30.349
this is the amount of data that it takes
for a human being to consume in a minute.

00:06:30.350 --> 00:06:37.000
So, text we have about 1 K, audio is a couple
of megabytes, video, standard video is,

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:43.629
a QuickTime kind of movie is 5
megabytes, a standard definition TV,

00:06:43.629 --> 00:06:47.709
10 megabytes, and high definition TV, 25 megabytes.

00:06:47.709 --> 00:06:55.370
So, you can see that as we put greater demands on the
quality of the information that is delivered to us,

00:06:55.370 --> 00:07:01.699
we also have a similar problem with the
amount of data that that actually consumes.

00:07:01.699 --> 00:07:06.120
And a good example of this is podcasting.

00:07:06.120 --> 00:07:14.680
When podcasting was starting in iTunes, we had Car Talk,
or something like Car Talk, which is an audio podcast,

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:23.250
and then the initial podcasts and video were sort of like
standard definition and so they were bigger, but not huge,

00:07:23.250 --> 00:07:29.649
and now we've seen the trend go towards high definition
podcasts, so we are having to be able to push large amounts

00:07:29.649 --> 00:07:34.639
of data, and the trend is always towards a bigger scale.

00:07:36.220 --> 00:07:38.840
So, we have this big content distribution problem.

00:07:38.839 --> 00:07:41.089
We have massive amounts of data.

00:07:41.089 --> 00:07:44.509
It has to be in a human consumable format.

00:07:44.509 --> 00:07:51.539
People don't want to have large pieces of data,
they want to have information that comes out of it.

00:07:51.540 --> 00:08:00.860
We have to distribute across large geographic areas because
that's where enterprises are, and we have multiple formats

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:05.960
because you need to be able to consume it on the
device where you need it, whether it's your iPod,

00:08:05.959 --> 00:08:10.159
your computer, and one format just doesn't work, right?

00:08:10.160 --> 00:08:12.460
It has to look good everywhere.

00:08:13.769 --> 00:08:15.560
So, someone must have solved this problem.

00:08:15.560 --> 00:08:19.870
Well, it just so happens, it's us.

00:08:19.870 --> 00:08:21.870
It's Apple.

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:29.149
So, in iTunes we believe we've solved a significant
