non-participants, the 52 percent of these non-participants,

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:24.759
the average age is 50, so clearly,
the future is with the participants.

00:20:29.210 --> 00:20:32.990
So, if we then look at the participants
and break that down a little,

00:20:32.990 --> 00:20:37.480
we can see they come into various different factions, right.

00:20:37.480 --> 00:20:39.779
So, we have the collectors.

00:20:39.779 --> 00:20:44.879
These are basically the people who create
the metadata, they create pages of links,

00:20:44.880 --> 00:20:49.920
and thinks like that to be able
to redirect and collect knowledge.

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:51.850
We have the joiners.

00:20:51.849 --> 00:20:55.219
These are people who participate in things
like Facebook, they read and publish blogs,

00:20:55.220 --> 00:20:58.880
and interestingly they're the youngest
of all the participators.

00:21:00.930 --> 00:21:10.610
Then we have the critics, these are people who make comments
on blogs, they post reviews, things of that nature.

00:21:10.609 --> 00:21:14.319
We then have the spectators, a big group of people.

00:21:14.319 --> 00:21:15.559
They're the audience.

00:21:15.559 --> 00:21:20.190
They're the people who are actually
consuming this experience.

00:21:20.190 --> 00:21:25.620
And then finally, of the categorized
group, we have the creators.

00:21:25.619 --> 00:21:29.619
These are the people who are actually generating
content, and they're, it's interesting,

00:21:29.619 --> 00:21:36.469
because they're the younger group and they're
pretty evenly split 50-50 male to female,

00:21:36.470 --> 00:21:42.370
but the other interesting fact is that
they are twice as likely to be Mac users.

00:21:42.369 --> 00:21:48.359
So, Mac users are twice as likely to create
content on the web than any other user.

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:59.470
Now, some of these Web 2.0 apps are actually
dominating their category, even so for example Wikipedia,

00:21:59.470 --> 00:22:07.259
the hits outnumber on Wikipedia a more
traditional encyclopedia application like Encarta,

00:22:07.259 --> 00:22:10.589
three, almost three and a half thousand to one.

00:22:11.650 --> 00:22:15.130
And Web 2.0 is really just exploding, right.

00:22:15.130 --> 00:22:24.410
It's twelve percent of all the U.S. web activity,
and has an almost 6X growth, 670 percent,

00:22:24.410 --> 00:22:28.160
over 6X growth in the last two years alone.

00:22:29.240 --> 00:22:36.519
If you look at something like YouTube, 18 to 24
are the age group of the most people who view,

00:22:36.519 --> 00:22:40.109
and the people who upload are in the age group of 35 to 45.

00:22:40.109 --> 00:22:46.659
So, this is the younger end of the spectrum,
so clearly Web 2.0 is the future.

00:22:49.960 --> 00:22:53.059
So, for presentation, what are the challenges here?

00:22:53.059 --> 00:22:55.419
We have a number of different development models.

00:22:55.420 --> 00:23:02.380
We're trying to maintain developer productivity, we
want to keep our administration costs under control.

00:23:06.369 --> 00:23:12.809
So, we clearly have traditional desktop applications
providing a great experience we want to leverage the web,

00:23:12.809 --> 00:23:17.960
and so hybrids are really a very
interesting direction to go.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:22.370
Using standards like AJAX, css, and
basically everything that's in WebKit.

00:23:22.369 --> 00:23:27.049
WebKit is a great supporter of
all the Web 2.0 standards.

00:23:27.049 --> 00:23:33.599
Which basically means that WebKit is the target platform,
which actually means that you'd have less testing, right.

00:23:33.599 --> 00:23:38.509
